{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2abbott_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604641/1945120801/0157.xml":{"full_text":"w Pitting ptm8\nWith Sunday Morning edition.\nTHEODORE W. NOYES, Editor.\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\nThe Evening Star Newspaper Company.\nMain Office: 11th St. and Pennsylvania Ave.\nNew York Office: 110 East 42d 8t.\nChicago Office: 436 North Michigan Ave.\nDelivered by Carrier\u2014Metropolitan Area.\nEffective October 1, 1944.\nRegular Edition. 4 Sundays. 5 Sundays.\nEvening and Sunday 90c Per mo. $1.00 per mo\nThe Evening Star 60c per month.\nThe Sunday Star 10c per copy\nNight Final Edition. 4 Sundays. 6 Sundays.\nNight Final and Sunday $1.00 mo. $1.10 mo.\nNight Final Star 76c Per month.\nRates by Mail\u2014Payable in Advance.\nAnywhere In United States.\n1 month, 6 months 1 year.\nEvening and Sunday $1.00 $6.00 $12.0(1\nThe Evening Star_ .76 4.00 8.00\nThe Sunday Star_ .60 2.50 6.00\nTelephone National 6000.\nEntered at the Pott Office. Washington. D. C..\nas second-class mail matter\nMember of the Associated Press.\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to\nthe use for republication of all news dispatches\ncredited to It or not otherwise credited in this\npaper and also the local news published herein\nAll rights of publication of sDeclal dispatches\nherein also are reserved.\nA\u20148 SATURDAY, December 8, 1945\nMore Light Needed\nOut of the welter of confusing and\nconflicting statements which have\nfollowed in the wake of the recent\nDistrict Jail break, it has become\nevident that only a thorough-going\npublic airing of all phases of the\njail problem\u2014a problem that Wash-\nington seems to have with it peren- j\nnially \u2014will clear the atmosphere\nand point the way for effective\nremedies. Shakeups in the jail staff,\nhowever necessary an impartial in\nvestigation may prove them to be,\ndo not of themselves provide any\nguarantee of a cure for the ills of\nWashington\u2019s outmoded penal estab\nlishment on the Eastern Branch.\nThere have been changes of person\nnel in the past, but prisoners con\ntinue to escape.\nThe troubles at the jail are deep\nrooted and the haphazard steps\nwhich have been taken over the\npast decade to eliminate them have\nresulted in superficial improvements\nthat fall far short of the needs.\nFundamentally, little has been done\nto provide a modern jail since former\nAttorney General Homer Cummings\npaid a surprise visit to the institu\ntion early in his career as heatl of\nthe Department of Justice and ex\npressed amazement over the \u201cshock\ning\u201d Inadequacy of the buildings and\nequipment. Since that time jail\nheads have come and gone and each\nof them has stressed the difficulty\nof running an efficient establish\nment under the conditions which\nmust be put up with at the old jail.\nThe present superintendent, Howard\nB. Gill\u2014who is now recommended\nfor dismissal by the Board of Public\nWelfare was appointed last year\nafter a committee of citizens headed\nby former United States Attorney\nLeo A. Rover had investigated the\njail and found it wanting in many\nrespects. Most of these defects had\nto do with conditions affecting\nmorale of the prisoners, but some of\nthem related to plant deficiencies\nhampering efficient administration\nof the jail.\nMr. Gill, in replying in part to the\nboard\u2019s charges of inefficiency, has\ndeclared that he repeatedly has\nasked for construction of walls, suit\nable gates and other improvements\ndesigned to prevent escapes, but has\nfailed to receive them. He points\nout that the Board of Public Wel\nfare\u2019s investigating committee which\nrecommended his dismissal had\n\u201cadopted\u201d some of his recommenda\ntions for safeguarding against jail\nbreaks, including appointment of\nthirty-one additional guards and\nconstruction of walls and gates. It\nmay well be that even without these\nimprovements, a more alert and effi\ncient jail staff could have prevented\nthe recent escapes. Certainly there\nappears to have been an inexcusable\ndelay in reporting the break to\npolice. But it is yet to be shown that\na high degree of personnel efficiency\nalone could forestall future at\ntempts. Certainly Mr. Gill is entitled\nto give his side of the case at a pub\nlic hearing, such as is proposed by\nMr. Rover in his capacity as spokes\nman for a civic group deeply con\ncerned with jail conditions. Out of\nsuch a forum may come not only\nconstructive suggestions for improv\ning the jail but, what is more im\nportant, concrete action to imple\nment the recommendations.\nAir-Minded Navy\nThe evolution of air power as a\ndominating influence in the Navy\u2019s\nover-all strategic planning continues\napace, as the high command re\nflects upon lessons of the campaigns\nlately concluded and seeks to adapt\nnaval warfare to the still-vague pat\nterns of an atomic age. As Secretary\nFc restal stressed not long ago in\nannouncing the appointment of\nVice Admiral Marc Mitscher, famed\ntask force commander, as deputy\nchief of naval operations for air, this\nIs indeed an aerial \"evolution.\u201d\nrather than a \u201crevolution.\u201d The de\nveloping importance of carrier war\nfare in the Pacific was recognized\nwith increasing clarity as the war\nstill progressed toward its decisive\nstages and the atomic bomb, deliv\nered as it was by air, has served to\naccelerate the trend.\nThe latest evidence of the Navy\u2019s\nair-mindedness is seen In Mr. For\nrestal\u2019s announcement of a new plan\nof Navy organization in top levels\nwhich will result in assignment of\nveteran naval aviators not only to\nhigh-policy posts at the Navy De\npartment but to important fleet\ncommands in the Pacific and Atlan\ntic. Under this plan, Admiral John\nH. Towers, the Navy\u2019s No. 1 aviator,\nwho learned to fly in the days of the\nWright brothers and Glenn Curtiss,\nwill become \u201cCincpac\u201d\u2014commander\nIn chief of the Pacific Fleet\u2014and\nAdmiral Mitscher will be made com\nmander of the Eighth Fleet, in the\nAtlantic. Three of the six key places\nin the office of the Chief of Naval\n\nOperations will go to flying admirals.\nThus, in contrast to the Army\u2019s\nplan of a separate air force, the\nNavy is moving*to integrate even\nfurther the surface and air co-ordi\nnates of its consolidated .fighting\nteam. In the integration process old\nconcepts of naval warfare are being\ndiscarded in favor of strategy and\ntactics in which air power assumes\nan all-important role. The evolu\ntion, although gradual, is nonethe\nless noteworthy and salutary.\nYamashita's Crime\nAfter what he himself describes\nas a fair trial. General Tomoyuki\nYamashita\u2014the \u201cTiger of Malaya\u201d\n\u2014has been sentenced to death by\nan American military commission in\nManila for the crime of having\nfailed to control his forces in such\na way as to prevent their terrible\natrocities in the Philippines.\nYamashita himself, as he con\ntended during his trial, may have\ntaken no personal or direct part in\nthe rape and slaughter, and it is\nconceivable\u2014though it seems highly\nimprobable\u2014that he was unaware of\nwhat was happening. But he was\nthe top commander of all Japanese\nforces in the Philippines, and he was\ntherefore responsible for everything\ndone by them.\nIt does not lessen his fundamental\nguilt to say that he remained per\nsonally aloof from the sadism and\nbutchery or that he did not know\nabout them. The blood on the hands\nof his subordinates was blood on his\nhands as well. If he did not know\nwhat they were doing, he should\nhave known. As their commander,\nit was his duty and responsibility to\nknow. One word from him might\nhave been enough to stop the terror\nbefore it started, and if he had is\nsued that word and done his best to\nhave it obeyed, he would not now be\na man condemned to be hanged.\nThe crime, the atrocity, personally\ncommitted by Yamashita was that\nhe neglected, willfully or otherwise,\nto exercise his authority as it should\nhave been exercised, and it was from\nthis negligence, fundamentally, that\nthe crimes and atrocities of his sub\nordinates flowed. The circumstances\nof the situation, as the American\ncommission has declared in sentenc\ning him, demanded that he provide\neffective control of his troops, but\nhe did not do this, and so the hor\nrifvintr hrnt.alit.ips tnrdr nlano artH\nwere, indeed, \"often methodically\nsupervised by Japanese officers.\u201d As\nthe top officer, therefore, the officer\nwho had the power to restrain all\nthose under him, he must be held at\nleast as accountable as any of his\nunderlings, and it is doubtful in the\nextreme that the logic of this find\ning will be declared invalid by the\nauthorities to whom he may yet\nappeal.\nIt is said that this sets a precedent\nin international law. If so, it is a\nmost wholesome precedent, and one\nto be marked well by present and\nfuture military commanders in every i\nland. It is a civilizing principle\nwhich our not too civilized world j\nshould be able to use to good advan\ntage in the years ahead.\nThere was nothing lazy about\nJerome Kern. A whole hour of his\nmusic on the radio will be a mere\nskimming of the cream of the long\nlist of real melodies he wrote.\nBreaking France's Veto\nSecretary of State Byrnes\u2019 an\nnouncement that the American\nGovernment contemplates drastic\naction to break the deadlock caused\nby French obstructionism over the\neconomic handling of the Reich\nsharpens the tension in this unfor\ntunate diplomatic issue.\nThe genesis of the present con\ntroversy goes back to the economic\nclauses of the Potsdam agreement\nmade last spring between the execu\ntive heads of America. Britain and\nthe Soviet Union, when the \"Big\nThree\u201d specifically provided that,\nduring the Allied occupation, Ger\nmany, though divided into separate\nmilitary zones, was to be treated as\n\u201con PPnnnmio unit M Hurinir tho on_\nsuing months it has become increas\ningly evident that such treatment is\nvitally necessary if economic chaos\nin the Reich is to be averted this\nwinter. That has been stressed in\nthe past fortnight by both the mili\ntary and civilian heads of our occu\npational authorities.\nFrance was not a party to the\nPotsdam agreement, having been\nexcluded from the conference de\nspite its vehement protests. France\nwas, however, subsequently admitted\nto the Allied Control Council in Ber\nlin and was assigned a zone of occu\ni pation in Western Germany. From\nthat moment, the French govern\nment began pressing for a definitive\nsettlement of Germany\u2019s western\nfrontier similar to that already\ntacitly admitted for Germany\u2019s east\nern borders. And France made it\nclear that she insisted on the per\nmanent severance of the Rhineland\nfrom the Reich and the establish\nment of an international authority\nover the kuhr which would set up an\neconomic wall between it and the\nrest of Germany. The French have\nmade it clear that they deem this\nvital for their future protection and\nthat they have as much right to\nsuch security as Russia and Poland\nhave to theirs. Denied this satisfac\nI tion, France has taken advantage of\nthe unanimity rule in the council\u2019s\nprocedure to veto every proposed\nmeasure for Germany\u2019s economic re\nhabilitation.\nWhat Secretary Byrnes meditates\nis a proposal to Britain and Russia\nthat they and the United States\ntreat their respective zones as an\neconomic unit, regardless of what\nFrance does in her relatively small\nzone. This would mean summarily\noverriding France\u2019s veto and imple\nmenting the economic agreement\nmade before she was admitted to the\ncontrol council. Such action might\nprecipitate a diplomatic crisis with\n\u2022\u2019v\nFranc e. It could also furnish a prec\nedent which Russia might not relish\nfor the ,UNO. Yet the threat of\neconomic chaos in Germany is so\nmenacing that there may be no\nalternative.\nAir-Sea Mystery\nThe mystery of what happened to\na missing formation of five Navy\ntorpedo planes in the Miami area\nlast Wednesday, and to a patrol\nplane sent in search of the group,\ncontinues to grow, despite efforts of\nhundreds of planes and scores of\nships to find the aircraft and the\ntwenty-seven men who were aboard\nthem.\nWhat sets thi$ apparent tragedy\napart from other noncombat acci\ndents is the fact that no distress call\nwas received from any of the six\nplanes, although all were equipped\nwith radio. Weather conditions dur\ning most of the fatal training ^ight\nwere moderate, but it was learned\nsubsequently that an unpredicted\nfreak \u201cdisturbance\u201d developed near\nMiami about the hour that the\nplanes last reported their position\nover the Atlantic.\nIf this sudden storm was to blame\nfor the disaster, it is hard to under\nstand why none of the planes was\nable to send out a distress call be\nfore crashing. There is the alterna\ntive possibility that the planes were\nflying in tight formation in the\ngathering darkness and plunged into\nthe sea in follow-the-leader fashion,\nthrough a miscalculation of the\nleader. This might account for\nthe failure to send an SOS. It\nwould not, however, explain the dis\naDDearance of the search plane sev\neral hours later. Here is an air-sea\nmystery which it is to be hoped the\nNavy will succeed in solving com\npletely, lest other flyers meet a\nsimilar fate.\nA traveling man who takes carrier\npigeons with him to send messages\nto his wife at home recently made\nthe headlines with the statement\nthat his plan was ideal. The birds,\nof course, co-operate in the conver\nsation by staying home when they\nget there and not returning with\nany back talk.\nPlans being discussed for the tomb\nof another unknown soldier are not\nnearly so important as plans to\nmake war itself unknown.\nThe war still is going on\u2014as far\nas the price of clothing is concerned.\nThis and That\nBy Charles E. Tracewell.\nThe modem mother often meets her\nmatch in the modem daughter.\nEven small daughters can do a sur\nprisingly good job at times.\nRuthie is 5.\nShe has beautiful wavy hair, eyes like\nstars and a nice friendly smile.\nFive is a very important age. When\nyou are 5 you are really getting up in\nthe world. Divided into the ages of\nolder folks, perhaps, 5 doesn\u2019t seem\nvery much, but this is just one view\npoint.\nA more important viewpoint is that\nbeing 5 is being big.\nRecently Ruthie\u2019s mother brought\nhome some packages that looked sur\nprisingly like Christmas gifts. That\nwasn\u2019t so very surprising, after all, for\nthat was what they were.\nThe child started to open them.\n\u201cThey are not to be opened now,\nRuthie,\u201d said her mother. \u201cThey are\nto be a surprise.\u201d\nNothing more was said. A day or two\nlater when her mother was away,\nRuthie was playing with a companion.\nCuriosity evidently got the best of them,\nfor they opened the big package on the\nshelf.\nIt had some pretty plastic dfshes\nwhich Ruthie immediately recognized as\njust designed for the playhouse. They\nplayed very happily with the new\ndishes for a long time, but finally grew\ntired as one must, even when 5 years\nold.\nThey put the dishes back on the\nsneu, dui not. in me dox, anu uiai was\nhow mother came to find them.\n\u201cRuthie,\u201d said her mother, in her\ncalmest manner, \"I want to talk to you\nabout the dishes.\u201d\n\u201cMother,\u201d said Ruthie, Just as calmly,\n\u201cI don\u2019t care to discuss the matter now.\u201d\n\nRuthie is the same young lady (she\nwas only 4 then) who decided that\nshe would like to go to a companion\u2019s\nhouse for lunch.\nWith the direct action of youth she\nimmediately came in and told her\nmother of her desire.\n\u201cBut, Ruthie, we don\u2019t go to people\u2019s\nhouses for lunch unless we are invited,\u201d\nreplied her mother.\nRuthie retired to the playhouse for\nconsultation, and the other children dis\nappeared for some time. On returning\nfrom the neighbor\u2019s house, her playmate\nannounced that Ruthie was now invited.\nFor some unknown reason, however,\nRuthie looked very downcast.\n\u201cYou had better get ready,\u201d said\nmother.\n\u201cBut, mother,\u201d spoke Ruthie, her face\ngrowing longer at every word, \u201cI don\u2019t\nthink I had better go because there is a\nbad dog down there, and you know I\nam afraid of dogs.\u201d\n\u201cThe dog won\u2019t hurt you.\u201d\n\u201cBut, mother,\u201d said Ruthie, \u201cthere is a\nbad boy who throws stones.\u201d\n\u201cThe maid will go with you and see\nthat neither the dog nor boy bothers\nyou.\u201d\n\u201cBut, mother, little Peggy will be lone\nsome without me. I think I\u2019d better\nstay with her.\u201d\nMother assured her her little sister\nwould be well taken care of in her ab\nsense.\nThe real reason for Ruthie\u2019s sudden\nreversal would soon come to light, her\nmother knew, and it soon did.\n\u201cBut, mother,\u201d wailed Ruthie, \u201cthey\ndon\u2019t have lunch till one and I\u2019m\nhungry ~lght now.\u201d\n\nLittle Peggy once swallowed a piece of\nevergreen tip which lodged in her throat.\nMother and the maid tried all the\ndodges to induce such a misplaced ar\nticle to come up, and sent Ruthie to\nask an experienced neighbor to come\nto the rescue.\n\u201cMay I come in?\u201d asked Ruthie, in\nher best manner.\n\u201cWhy, certainly,\" smiled the neighbor,\nshowing the little girl to a seat.\nThey talked pleasantly of many\nthings, and finally Ruthie asked the\nhostess if she could come over to her\nhouse.\nThinking Ruthie\u2019s mother merely\nwanted to show her something, the good\nneighbor washed her hands and combed\nher hair, and then joined Ruthie in\nwalking across the street.\nThey got there just as Peggy, held up\nside down and thumped soundly on the\nback, disgorged the evergreen.\n\nLetters to The Star\nDiscusses Liquor Advertising and\nIts Potential Reactions\nTo the Editor of The St\u00bbr:\nIt was my understanding, a few years\nago, that the liquor dealers, along with\nme, were horrified at the effects of a\nlaw known as \u201cprohibition.\u201d What has\nchanged their attitude? I take for\ngranted that this attitude has changed,\nbecause I see clearly, along with other\nobservant people, that they are making\nherculean and frantic efforts to bring it\nback, with reinforcements. They are\nbuying beautiful and expensive adver\ntisements in most of the magazines and\nother publications to usher in an era in\nwhich everybody drinks whisky and\nwhose rising generation will get the im\npression that intoxicating liquor, rather\nthan bread, is the staff of life. They\npresent pictures of men of all ages (ex\ncept the very young, and the pictures\nare not wholly representative unless you\ninclude some of these latter; engaged\nin swigging whisky.\nNow, I never have been a crusader.\nBut I love my fellow men and don\u2019t\nwant to see them do things that de\ngrade them and put them on the back\ntrack toward the cave dweller. Mod\nerate drinking harms no one. But the\neffort of liquor dealers to persuade\neverybody, including those who would\nspeedily become hard drinkers, to get\nbusy buying and imbibing is a direct\ndisservice to the human race. They are\ndoing all in their power to cause enough\nhuman wrecks to start mothers and\nfathers and friends working to stop their\ndestructive course. And by the time\nenuugn men s ana women s sons ana\ndaughters have ruined themselves phy\nsically and/or mentally, or both, by\nthe time enough young women have\nbeen morally destroyed through partici\npation in drinking parties, by the time\nseveral thousands of people\u2019s best be\nloved children have been killed by\ndrunken drivers, by the time drink-in\ncited moral depredations have become\nso pronounced\u2014so glaring\u2014that even\npeople who do some moderate drinking\nshall have been roused to frenetic hate\nagainst liquor\u2014the liquor dealers will be\nno more able to stem that tide toward\na prohibition law than King Canute\nwas able to keep the tide back from the\nshore.\nThe next prohibition attack\u2014and, I\nrepeat, it is coming\u2014will be far more\ndesperate and resistless than the pre\nvious one. There will be greater\ngrievance and more fighters. It will be\nparticipated in by people who drink\nsome of them drunkards past the power\nof controlling alone their diseased ap\npetites, hellbent on getting rid of the\ntemptation the liquor dealers have so\nenticingly furnished. It will be an army\nof mothers, fathers, husbands, wives,\nbrothers, sisters, sons, daughters, all\nof whose sacredest of Interests have\nbeen brutally violated.\nThe liquor dealers should think this\nover. Their present policy is stupid.\nSTRICKLAND GILLILAN.\nSees Democracy in Discard\nTo tile iditor of The Stir:\nIn the current agitation of the Zion\nist question, the most fundamental and\nfar-reaching issue seems to be ignored\nby both sides.\nBy insisting upon a Jewish state in\nPalestine the Zionists propose a death\nblow to the basic principle of democ\nracy, which is government by majority.\nHalf a million newcomers in the\nland insist that Palestine be turned\nover to them as a Jewish state, ruling\nout a million Arabs, who have dwelt in\nPalestine for thousands of years.\nIf a minority is to be given sovereignty\nover a majority, then democracy goes\nout of the window.\nIncidentally, all colonial empires will\nbe justified. WILLIAM T. ELLIS.\nSwarthmore, Pa.\nCongressional Record \u2018Illegal\u2019?\nTo the Editor of The Star:\nThe Congressional Record still in\ncludes China in the ninth judicial\ncircuit. As Mr. Justice Douglas is the\njustice assigned to this circuit, I wrote\nhim a letter recently about it, and\nhere is his reply through his secretary,\nEdith Waters: \"Your letter of November\n15, 1945, to Mr. Justice Douglas hat\nbeen received. The answer to your in\nquiry is found in the report of the\nJudicial Conference, September, 1945,\np. 29, which stated that the United\nStates Court for China \u2018ceased to exist\non May 20, 1943, in consequence of the\nfraofu hotnrflon tHo TTnitoH Qtatoc onH\nChina abolishing extraterritorial juris\ndiction of the United States in China.\u2019\nIt is obvious, therefore, that the inclu\nsion of China within the ninth Judicial\ncircuit in the Congressional Record for\nNovember 8, 1945, was an inadvertence.\u2019\u2019\nThere, now, the Supreme Court has\nspoken, and yet the Congressional Rec\nord continues this illegality! Will the\nCongress listen to the Supreme Court\nl or wont it? HENRY STONER.\nVeterans-Unions Affiliations\nTo the Editor ol The Star:\nI want to commend for reading and\nrereading the article in The Star of\nDecember 1 by Maj. George Fielding\nEliot in which the major suggested\nto veterans of the recent war that they\navoid being \u2018\u2018used\u2019\u2019 by selfiish interests.\nMaj. Eliot had immediate reference\nto the fact that it is all too easy to\nfind new veterans\u2019 organizations which\nwill accept funds to promote purposes\n1 far afield. This fact was well developed\nin the national convention of one such\ngroup when it was shown that money\nfrom Texas was being used to oppose\nlabor unions.\nThe fact that we have veterans in\nunions and union members in veterans\u2019\ngroups is sufficient reason for all to\nstand up and be counted for those\nthings which mean the most for the\nmajority of our citizens.\nLabor groups will continue to as\nsist veterans in all practical ways. For\nexample, I cite the campaign now being\nwaged by labor unions for immediate\nemergency housing programs to meet\nthe needs of vetetans.\nFOSTER J. PRATT,\nSecretary-treasurer, Government Em\nployes\u2019 Council, A. F. of L.\nIsolationism Can Threaten\nrrom the Retina Leader-Post.\nIsolationism has its roots in the minds\nand ways of American people. As long\nas it is there, there will be men and\nwomen ready to lead isolationist Ameri\ncans, express their ideas and mold them\ninto concrete form. And little less does\nisolationism still exist in Canada. The\nwar demonstrated, through the rise of\nthe Bloc Populaire and other groups,\nthat isolationism can grow and threat\nen. While events In Canada in recent\nmonths have blunted the Isolationists,\nthere can easily arise time and oppor\ntunity for them to reassert and spread\ntheir views.\nThis Changing World\nConstantine Brown\nThe American policies on the revival\nof world trade, to which the British have\nsubscribed and which the two nations\nwill advocate at the forthcoming .In\nternational Trades Congress, provide\nwhat can well be called a Magna Carta\nof commerce. They are in the best\ntradition of that economic liberalism\nwhich was preached for more than a\ndecade by former Secretary of State\nCordell Hull.\nYet diplomatic realists, reading over\nthe provisions set out in the American\nmemorandum, spotted at once several\npoints which are bound to raise seri\nous controversy. If they are accepted\nat all by some of the big commercial\npowers, it will be only after long and\nspirited argument and in consideration\nof either concessions or economic\nthreats from the United Stales.\nOne section likely to meet strenuous\nobjections from Soviet Russia and the\nEastern European countries which are\nnow being impressed into its economic\npolitical sphere is that relating to state\ntrading.\nIt should be remembered that all\ntrading in Russia is state trading. Even\nthe little sidewalk stalls that sell candy\nand ice cream are owned by trusts.\nInternational buying is done by gov\nernment organizations set up in each\nforeign country for that purpose. In\nthe United States, for instance, it is\nhandled in normal times by Amtorg,\nwhich is merely a contraction of the\nRussian words for American Trading\nCo.\n\nThis section provides, with other\nthings, that members of the proposed\nInternational Trade Organization en\ngaged in state trading \u201cshould accord\nequality of treatment to all other mem\nbers.\u201d\nTo this end, the proposal specifies\nthat \"state-trading enterprises shall be\ninfluenced solely by commercial con\nsiderations, such as price, quality, mar\nketability, transportation and terms of\npurchase or sale.\u201d More important, the\nsection provides that in return for tarifT\nconcessions made bv nations having a\nsystem of private trade, those having\nstate control shall agree to a \"global\npurchase arrangement.\u201d Under this ar\nrangement they would agree to purchase\nfrom members of the ITO on a \"non\ndiscriminatory\" basis \u201cproducts valued\nat not less than an aggregate amount\nto be agreed upon.\"\nMoreover, the proposals provide that\nmembers of the ITO who have state\ntrading systems \u201cagree not to create\nprotective margins greater than the\ntariffs which may have been negotiated\nin regard to those products.\u201d\nThe acceptance of these provisions by\nRussia would mean a sharp break with\nmany of its former practices. In the\npast the men who run the Soviet Com\nmissariat of Foreign Trade have been\nwily shoppers. Buying in great bulk,\nthey have looked the world over care\nfully for bargains. One of their prime\nconsiderations has been long-term cred\nits.\nNor have politics been forgotten.\nRussia has often placed its orders\nwhere it wanted to build up strong\npolitical ties.\n\nAlthough the British government has\nagreed to the proposals, two sections of\nthem are sure to arouse sharp antagon\nism among certain British business\ncircles.\nThose are the sections providing for\nthe restriction of cartels and the aboli\ntion of preferential tariffs, which ap\npear to spell the doom of the empire\npreference rates drawn up at the Ot\ntawa Conference.\nA large section of British industry\nlong has operated through cartels and\nconsiders them highly beneficial. Al\nready there has been an outcry among\nan important sector of the British press\nagainst American efforts to obtain an\nending of the Ottawa rates.\nBut the United States will enter the\ntrade conference with two strong cards.\nFirst, the recently passed reciprocal\ntrade act, permitting a reduction of 50\nper cent in existing rates (which would\nmean a total cut of 75 per cent on some\nof the Smoot-Hawley rates in countries,\nwhere we already have reciprocal trade\nagreements) places this country in a\nstrong bargaining position.\nEven more important is the fact that,\nAmerica today is the world's banker and\nthat virtually every commercial nation\n\u2014including Russia\u2014Is looking to the\nUnited States for loans These two fac\ntors place the United States in a strong\nposition to obtain the liberalized trade\npolicies to which the administration is\ncommitted.\nThe Political Mill\nBy Gould Lincoln\nCHICAGO. Dec. 8 \u2014Capt. Harold E.\nStassen, U. S. N. R., out of the service\nafter serving in the Pacific as aide to\nAdmiral Halsey, in the opinion of manv\nmembers of the Republican National\nCommittee, is a leader today for the\nRepublican presidential nomination. A\nsurvey of the committee, as it met in\nChicago for a two-dav session, gives\nthe distinct impression that the former\nGovernor of Minnesota, if the Repub\nlican National Convention were held\ntoday, would be the outstanding candi\ndate for the nomination.\nNext to Capt. Stassen. the same sur\nvey places former Gov. John Bricker of\nOhio in second place. Gov. Dewey of\nNew York, the defeated candidate of\n1944, admittedly has lost ground. He is\ncounted out of the race by many of the\ncommittee members as they look for\nward to 1948. Some of those who ar\ndently supported him for the nomina\ntion last year have become critical. They\ncriticize Gov. Dewey for the manner of\ni his campaign last year\u2014but, most of\nall, they insist it would be a mistake\nto renominate a defeated candidate for\nPresident\u2014urging that the Republican\nparty has never made such a nomina\ntion.\nOddly enough, some of those who\nmake this argument do not take into\naccount the fact that Mr. Bricker. as\nwell as Gov. Dewey, was a defeated\ni candidate in 1944. The difference, they\nsay, between the position of Gov. Dewey\nand of Mr. Bricker lies in the fact that\nGov. Dewey was the head of the na\ntional ticket and therefore the same\nargument does not run against a 1948\npresidential nomination for Mr. Bricker.\n\nThat Dewey sentiment still exists,\nhowever, in some States is admitted\u2014\nfor example, in Wisconsin. If Gov.\nDewey is renominated and re-elected\nGovernor of New York next year\u2014and\nshould win by a substantial margin, no\ndoubt there would be a recrudescence\nof Dewey support. But his victory prob\nably would have to be by a good margin\nif this were to happen. In any event,\nif Mr. Dewey is re-elected Governor and\nretains control of Republican* politics\nin the Empire State, he and his follow\ners will have a good deal to say about\nthe choice of a presidential nominee\u2014\neven if Dewey himself is out of that\npicture. New York Republicans are\nclose-mouthed about a presidential\nnominee at this stage. They are not\nthrowing in the sponge for Gov. Dewey,\nnor are they turning their affections\nto any other candidate.\nNext to Messrs. Stassen. Bricker and\nDewey, there was more talk among the\nRepublican committee men for Senator\nVandenberg of Michigan and Senator\nSaltonstall of Massachusetts than for\nany others. The Michigan Senator has\nmade a deep impression on Republicans\nbecause of his constructive leadership,\non many subjects but particularly on\nforeign policy, in the Senate and at the\nUnited Nations Conference held in San\nFrancisco when the United Nations\ncharter was drafted.\nSenator Vandenberg himself, however,\nhas indicated no desire whatever to be\ncome a candidate for President. He is\nup for re-election next year, and bar\nring some political accident should win\nhandily. The Democrats have no strong\ncandidate, even were Senator Vanden\nber not personally popular with the\nvoters of the State The speculation is\nthat, if he is re-elected, Mr. Vanden\nberg would prefer to remain a Senator\nwith the probability he would become\nSecretary of State if a Republican were\nchosen President in 1948.\n\nSenator Saltonstall is highly regarded.\nTo Republicans generally he represents\nthe best that comes out of New England.\nAs of today he is by all odds Massa\nchusetts\u2019 first choice for the presidential\nnomination and he probably will have\nsupport in some of the other Northeast\nern States, Massachusetts Republi\ncans. however, are reported to be more\nfriendly to Capt. Stassen than they have\nbeen in the past. They will have an\nopportunity to look him over when he\ngoes to Boston to make an address at a\nRepublican dinner in the near future.\nMr. Bricker, too, has some support in\nthe Bay State.\nIf a military man is to have a chance\nat the Republican nomination, Kansas\nand other Midwest States are prepared\nto go strongly for Gen. Eisenhower,\nAllied commander in Europe and. more\nrecently. Chief of Staff of the United\nStates Army. There is a feeling among\ncommitteemen, however, that Gen.\nEisenhower will prefer to stick to his\nlife\u2019s profession\u2014that of arms\u2014rather\nthan to enter the political arena.\nGen. MacArthur. should he elect to go\ninto politics after he leaves Japan,\nwould have his supporters, too, among\nthe committeemen. But in his case also\ngrave doubts are expressed he would\nseek a presidential nomination.\nThe Republicans stress the idea that\nit is too early to talk definitely about\na presidential candidate to run in 1948.\nTheir immediate task, they say, is to\nclean up the congressional election next\nyear. Nevertheless, they do express\ntheir opinions about potential presi\ndential nominees.\nWar Leaders and Pay\ny\nBy Maj. George Fielding Eliot\nThere's a little matter of justice and\nI common decency to which the American\npeople ought to give their attention.\nIt\u2019s the matter of seeing to it that\nour great commanders of this war shall\nhave a reasonable provision lor their old\nage, as they retire from active service.\nDp you know what will happen to\nthem under present arrangements?\ni Messrs. Marshall. King, Arnold,\nI Leahy, Eisenhower, MacArthur, Nimitz\n\u2014the five-star Generals of the Army\nand fleet admirals\u2014will all. on retire\nment, receive only the retired pay of\nmajor generals or rear admirals, and\nno allowances: that is, $500 a month.\nOur great Chief of Staff, George C.\nMarshall, will retire on the same pay\nj as hundreds of officers who served in\nsubordinate positions at home and\nabroad, or who retired before the war\neven began. The commander in chief\nof the fleet, Ernest J. King, will find\nthat his countrymen have no more\ngrateful recollection of his services than\nthey have for those of some obscure\nj rear admiral: Or at least no more prac\ntical expression of gratitude.\n\nThese seven men have not only served\ntheir country with exceptional skill and\ndevotion: they have, by their wise lead\nership, saved the lives of uncountable\nthousands of our young men, for they\nhave given us the best commanded war\nin all our history, the one war in which\nit may definitely be said that there have\nbeen no major blunders which have\nhad to be paid for in wasted blood.\nTrue, Gen. Marshall now has a tem\nporary job as the President\u2019s special\nenvoy to China, but that will not affect\nhis retired pay, and he is already past\nthe retirement age and cannot be re\ntained on active duty after the legal\nexpiration of the pmsent state of war.\nGens. MacArthur and Arnold, Admirals\nKing and Leahy, are also past the legal\nretirement age and must retire very\nsoon. Gen. Eisenhower and Admiral\nNimitz have a few years left before\ntheir retirement will be due, but their\nprospects are no better when that time\ndoes come.\nIt is high time, therefore, to do some\nthing more practically effective than\nmedals and kind words to give these\ngreat leaders assurance of reasonable\ncomfort in their well-earned years of\nrest. There\u2019s good precedent for so\ndoing. After the Civil War, for ex\nample, the grades of general and lieu\ntenant general were created on the\nactive list of the Army as special re\nwards for Gens. Grant and Sherman,\nat substantial increases in pay. After\nthe World War, a grateful Congress\ncreated the rank of general of the\narmies for Gen. Pershing, at a life\ntime salary of $13,500 per year, plus\nallowances of $8,000.\n\nThe Senate has taken some action In\nthis matter, by passing the bill S-1354\nwhich would continue for life the\nactive-duty pay now received by our\nfive-star officers. That would mean\nthat they would continue, after retire\nment, to get their allowances for ra\ntions and quarters and the \u201cpersonal\nmoney allowance\u201d which now marks the\ndifference between their active-duty pay\nand that of a major general. Their\nmonthly rate of income would thus be\n$1,225 instead of the $500 which is now\nin prospect for them.\nBut this bill has been held up for\nmonths in the Military Affairs Com\nmittee of the House of Representatives,\nwhere it has run into opposition be\ncause some of the members are saying\n\u201cit will set a precedent and will cost a\nlot of money,\" while others say \u201cbut the\nGI has no such favored position,\u201d and\nstill others \"maybe some of these fel\nlows will be found to have had some\nthing to do with the Pearl Harbor\ndisaster.\u201d\nIt seems to this writer that it is about\ntime to put an end to this stupidity, to\nblast this bill out of the committee and\nget it to a vote. Several of the officers\nconcerned are about to retire, and time\nis short. The only way to blast the bill\nloose is. for the constituents of the com\nmittee members to let them know how\nthe folks back home feel about the mat\nter. In fact, all Congress members ought\nto know about this.\nA\nChange of U. S. Policy\nSeen in British Loan\nWorld Economic Stability to Be\nAided By Move, Says Writer\nBy David Lawrence\nThere\u2019s an extraordinary principle in\nvolved in the proposed loan by the\nUnited States to Great Britain. All\nprevious intergovernmental loans of\nany size have been made during a war\nin which the ally or allies helped our\ncause.\nThis is the first time during a period\nof peace that a loan has been offered\neither for the specific purpose of re\nhabilitation and reconstruction or as a\nmeans of promoting economic stability\nin the world.\nSuch a step, viewed in its broader\naspects, involves a constructive change\nof policy and the beginning of a more\nintimate period of interdependence than\nhas heretofore existed between the\nUnited States and Great Britain.\nThere will be, of course, much snip\ning at the loan and considerable oppo\nsition both in Congress and in the\nBritish Parliament. But the loan will\nbe approved eventually by both, because\nit is imperative that such financial aid\nbe given in order to prevent the disin\ntegration of the entire European eco\nnomic structure and particularly the\nimpairment of the economic strength\nof the whole British Empire.\nU. S. as World Banker.\nThe British Commonwealth of States\nbuys large quantities of American goods.\nA private banker always shows concern\nfor the businesses that buy and sell\nin Ul\u00bb rTU- T Tn J\nStates as a world banker' is showing\ngenuine concern for the future of world\ntrade and commerce.\nThis, however, is not due to any de\nsire on the part of the United States\nGovernment to make money out of the\ntransaction, but to a desire instead to\npromote business and trade for the\nAmerican producers whose surpluses will\nshortly be a matter of worry, especially\nas unemployment will increase unless\nmarkets for American production are\nenlarged.\nThe reason why an interest rate was\naffixed was because the lending oper\nation is a business transaction between\ngovernments and not an act of philan\nthropy or altruism. The United States\npays slightly more interest in borrow\ning from the American people, so it is\nnatural that an interest charge paid\nby Britain should virtually offset the\nAmerican Government's expense in bor\nrowing\nBut even if there were no interest\npaid, it would be to the advantage of\nthe United States to make the loan. If\nBritain suffers an economic collapse,\nthere is no hope for the continent of\nEurope to recover. Chaos in the eco\nnomic world means more opportunities\nfor Communism and Socialism and\nFascism depending on what the dema\ngogues can do in various areas to per\nsuade the victimized peoples that only\nthrough totalitarian methods can a\nwav out be found for them.\nThis was the basis on w\u2019hich Hitler\nism began in Germany. Economic chaos\nusually breeds the conditions that make\ndemagoguery and dictatorships possible.\nSimple Prudence.\nNo one can foresee the political fu\nture of Europe today. All that can be\nassumed is that Great Britain is likely\nto remain a friend in need. Her terri\ntory' became our main base of opera\ntions against Germany. Without Brit\nain\u2019s steadfast defense, Hitler might\nhave captured that base and marched\nsouthward to the west coast of Africa\nto begin his trans-Atlantic operations\nagainst the Panama Canal and South\nAmerica.\nThere are many persons who believe\nthat within a few years another war\nmay be shaping up in the world. Whether\ntheir beliefs are fantastic or not, it\nis simple prudence for the United States\nto do all in her power in the imme\ndiate future to keep the British Em\npire from economic disintegration.\nThe precedent, however, is even more\nimportant with respect to other coun\ntries. America, to be sure, has a huge\npublic debt already, but she will have,\na much bigger one to face if another\nwar ensues in a few years. Hence loans\nto other countries for reconstruction\npurposes may be expected. A loan to\nRussia has been discussed. It is a pos\nsibility. If this is going to help Russia\nto rebuild and take her place as a\nsatisfied partner in the family of na\ntions, it may be the best way to assure\nthe economic conditions that will guar\nantee peace.\nThe United States has spent many\nbillions for destructive purposes. It has\nembarked now on a policy of lending\nfor constructive purposes. The Con\ngress will be importuned to defeat these\nloan agreements, but if the people real\nly have steered away from isolation and\nthe United States is to play a role of\ninternational helpfulness, then the\nloans will be approved as a logical corol\nlary to our decision to become a part\nof the United Nations Organization.\n(Rpnrnrliirtinn Riehte PeeerveH\nMust Work Both Ways\nFrom the Toronto Telegram.\nAgreements negotiated between em\nployers and labor can have a stabilizing\ninfluence on industry only so long as\nthere is good faith on both sides. If\neither reneges on the pledged word there\nis the makings of a disturbance which\nis to the detriment of the community.\nIt is time to consider whether the pro\nvision for compulsory collective bargain\ning sufficiently safeguards agreements\nwhich have been arrived at. There is\nnot much difficulty in making a penalty\nattachable against an employer. It\nshould be equally easy to attach union\nfunds. The penalty in either case\nshould be heavy enough to intimate that\nan agreement, once reached, cannot be\nbroken with impunity.\nZodiac\nJVow as the earth wheels toward its\nmorning,\nHere in the clear stillness of a frost\nrimed night,\nThe vast clockwork of stars descends\nthe western heavens;\nOne by one familiar constellations fall\nfrom sight.\nThe white net of the Pleiades, the sail\ning stars,\nAnd charging Taurus with red Alde\nbaran\u2019s fiery eye;\nOrion\u2019s glittering armor and diamond\nSirius at heel;\nImplacably the stars and hours slip by.\nImplacably and swiftly they close the\nledger of a day,\nSilent and final as the very frost upon\nthe grass;\nThis silver architecture of the night is\ncrumbled now\nTo silver sand that settles in Time's\nhour glass.\nFREDERICK KB RIGHT.","height":"31752","width":"22360"}}
